<li id="cite_note-34"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.cato.org/university/module10.html" class="external text" title="http://www.cato.org/university/module10.html" rel="nofollow">"The Achievements of Nineteenth-Century Classical Liberalism"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.cato.org/university/module10.html" class="external free" title="http://www.cato.org/university/module10.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.cato.org/university/module10.html</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=The+Achievements+of+Nineteenth-Century+Classical+Liberalism&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cato.org%2Funiversity%2Fmodule10.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Capitalism"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span>
<blockquote>
<p>Although the term "liberalism" retains its original meaning in most of the world, it has unfortunately come to have a very different meaning in late twentieth-century America. Hence terms such as "market liberalism," "classical liberalism," or "libertarianism" are often used in its place in America.</p>
</blockquote>
